<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How Hook-and-String Systems Work</h2>

  <p>
    A hook anchors a length of string from an overhead support down to the plant. The tomato vine is then clipped or wrapped around the string as it grows.
  </p>

  <p>
    This creates a vertical support system that:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>keeps plants upright</li>
    <li>improves airflow</li>
    <li>makes harvesting easier</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    It’s simple and effective — at least early on.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Where This System Starts to Struggle</h2>

  <p>
    Unlike roller hooks, fixed hook-and-string setups don’t allow easy lowering. As plants grow taller:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>they approach the greenhouse ceiling</li>
    <li>stems become harder to manage</li>
    <li>harvesting gets less convenient</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This is where many growers switch to a “lower and lean” approach or accept reduced manageability.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Makes a Good Hook-and-String Setup</h2>

  <h3>Strong Hook Construction</h3>
  <p>
    Must support the weight of mature plants over time.
  </p>

  <h3>Durable String</h3>
  <p>
    Should resist stretching and breaking under load.
  </p>

  <h3>Consistent Tension</h3>
  <p>
    Prevents sagging and keeps plants stable.
  </p>

  <h3>Secure Attachment</h3>
  <p>
    The overhead support must handle long-term stress.
  </p>
</section>

